-cell-article-t.webp" type="image/webp"><source media="(min-width: 568px)" srcset="https://cdn.the-scientist.com/assets/articleNo/71177/aImg/50156/epithelial-cell-article-t.jpg" type="image/jpeg"><source media="(max-width: 400px)" srcset="https://cdn.the-scientist.com/assets/articleNo/71177/aImg/50156/epithelial-cell-article-s.webp" type="image/webp"><source media="(max-width: 400px)" srcset="https://cdn.the-scientist.com/assets/articleNo/71177/aImg/50156/epithelial-cell-article-s.jpg" type="image/jpeg"><source media="(max-width: 567px)" srcset="https://cdn.the-scientist.com/assets/articleNo/71177/aImg/50156/epithelial-cell-article-m.webp" type="image/webp"><source media="(max-width: 567px)" srcset="https://cdn.the-scientist.com/assets/articleNo/71177/aImg/50156/epithelial-cell-article-m.jpg" type="image/jpeg"><img src="https://cdn.the-scientist.com/assets/articleNo/71177/aImg/50156/epithelial-cell-article-t.jpg" alt="Epithelial cells and fungal spores are marked with fluorescent dyes. Cells have an irregular shape and are shown in green and blue colors. Spores are spherical in shape and are labeled green if they are surrounded by p11 protein. A protein in mature phagosomes is labeled violet." title="Epithelial cells and fungal spores are marked with fluorescent dyes. Cells have an irregular shape and are shown in green and blue colors. Spores are spherical in shape and are labeled green if they are surrounded by p11 protein. A protein in mature phagosomes is labeled violet." loading="lazy"></picture></a></figure></section><section class="text flex flex-col"><header><a href="/news-opinion/fungal-spores-hijack-a-host-protein-to-escape-death-71177" target="_self"><div class="h3 max-2-lines l-h-3">Fungal Spores Hijack a Host Protein to Escape Death</div></a></header><main><div class="displayAuthorAndTime"><span class="h6">Mariella Bodemeier Loayza Careaga, PhD </span><span class="h6"> | Jun 20, 2023</span><span class="h6"> | 3 min read</span></div><div class="max-3-lin